                                p.recipie-subTitle.mb-1 What does "Makhlouta" mean?
                                p.recipie-ingredient.pt-2.mb-0  Makhlouta literally means mixed. This typical villager dish can't get any easier. Just like it's name, it's a mixture of the grains and beans in your pantry, cooked in a pot.
                                p.recipie-ingredient.pt-2.mb-0  Fawzieh Boutros guides us step by step to make this recipe, along green fava beans with coriander, another villagers' recipe of spring time. 
                            .col-12.p-0.m-0.pt-2
                                p.recipie-subTitle.mb-1 Method
                                p.recipie-ingredient.pt-2.mb-0   After soaking the grains and beans overnight, strain and pour into a pressure cooker (Presto).
                                p.recipie-ingredient.pt-2.mb-0  Meanwhile, fry the onions until golden brown. After the beans are done, pour the onions with their oil on the bean mix, add salt and cumin, stir, and simmer for 10-15 mins. Turn the heat off and drizzle with some olive oil. 
